61
00:02:45,425 --> 00:02:54,630
Yes. Okay. So this talk is really about branching dialogue and the sort of challenges that come up with branching dialogue.

62
00:02:55,510 --> 00:02:59,812
Branching dialogue is not necessary. It kind of goes without saying, but I thought it needed to be addressed.

63
00:03:00,052 --> 00:03:02,394
It's not necessary or even desirable for lots of games.

64
00:03:02,734 --> 00:03:05,235
There are a lot of different styles of dialogue that you can approach in a game.

65
00:03:05,755 --> 00:03:09,437
These are the three sort of broad categories that I identified when I was preparing this talk.

66
00:03:09,837 --> 00:03:11,458
The first is linear or cinematic.

67
00:03:12,639 --> 00:03:15,120
arguably the most common that you'll see in games, especially nowadays.

68
00:03:16,461 --> 00:03:18,682
Sort of exemplified by games like the Uncharted series.

69
00:03:19,422 --> 00:03:21,804
The story is written, the characters are established,

70
00:03:21,904 --> 00:03:24,765
you aren't really, the player doesn't really have agency in how those

71
00:03:25,166 --> 00:03:27,347
characters interact with each other or how the story unfolds.

72
00:03:27,807 --> 00:03:30,369
It's a cinematic experience, writing's great, looks awesome,

73
00:03:30,949 --> 00:03:33,010
and the focus is really on the gameplay and you're just,

74
00:03:33,070 --> 00:03:34,751
the cinematic storytelling and the dialogue

75
00:03:35,311 --> 00:03:37,773
is there to serve a narrative function, it's not about player agency.

76
00:03:38,433 --> 00:03:39,914
Totally valid, cool thing to do.

77
00:03:40,988 --> 00:03:45,770
Another way of approaching dialogue is what I call keyword or subject dialogue.

78
00:03:46,350 --> 00:03:48,451
This is also not really about player agency.

79
00:03:48,471 --> 00:03:51,032
This isn't about saying to the player, you get to shape the story.

80
00:03:51,452 --> 00:03:53,993
It's about saying to the player, hey, do you want to learn more about this setting?

81
00:03:54,013 --> 00:03:55,253
Do you want to learn more about this world?

82
00:03:55,574 --> 00:03:57,036
Do you want to trigger this quest now?

83
00:03:57,476 --> 00:04:02,162
And so a game like the Diablo series uses this where you have a list of things to talk

84
00:04:02,222 --> 00:04:06,107
about and the player is really just saying like, tell me about this thing, tell me about

85
00:04:06,127 --> 00:04:07,289
this thing, tell me about this thing.

86
00:04:07,709 --> 00:04:11,915
So again, it's not about granting player agency, it's really about allowing the player to make

87
00:04:11,935 --> 00:04:14,278
a choice as to when they want to receive any bit of narrative content.

88
00:04:15,623 --> 00:04:17,784
What this talk is about, though, is about branching trees.

89
00:04:18,264 --> 00:04:23,326
This is dialogue where you have menus of options presented in a variety of ways,

90
00:04:23,746 --> 00:04:28,388
where the dialogue can flow, branch out, branch out even more, circle back on itself.

91
00:04:29,048 --> 00:04:32,189
Ideally, it's producing gameplay changes, it's producing story changes.

92
00:04:34,002 --> 00:04:36,123
It's not a whole lot of companies necessarily do this.

93
00:04:36,263 --> 00:04:37,184
I'm glad so many of you came.

94
00:04:37,224 --> 00:04:38,664
I wasn't sure how broad the appeal would be.

95
00:04:39,104 --> 00:04:41,625
But obviously companies like Bioware sell it at Black Isle.

96
00:04:42,065 --> 00:04:43,066
We did it back at Black Isle.

97
00:04:43,126 --> 00:04:44,586
We continue to do it at Obsidian.

98
00:04:44,947 --> 00:04:45,927
Bethesda also does it.

99
00:04:46,007 --> 00:04:48,668
I'm sure there are other companies that do it as well.

100
00:04:49,048 --> 00:04:52,710
But it's a tricky thing, and that's why I'm having this talk.

101
00:04:55,182 --> 00:04:57,787
So someone might ask, why even use branching trees?

102
00:04:57,827 --> 00:04:58,568
What's the advantage?

103
00:04:59,350 --> 00:05:01,373
You can get all sorts of cool cinematic stuff and cool

104
00:05:01,393 --> 00:05:03,036
character development with good voice acting and

105
00:05:03,076 --> 00:05:04,479
everything in a purely cinematic view.

106
00:05:04,559 --> 00:05:05,902
Why even use branching trees?

107
00:05:06,323 --> 00:05:07,885
There are a few very good reasons for this.

108
00:05:09,168 --> 00:05:11,871
First is, you get to grant story agency to the player.

109
00:05:12,071 --> 00:05:13,512
You get to say to the player, hey, you know what?

110
00:05:13,913 --> 00:05:16,355
You have some role in defining where the story goes

111
00:05:16,716 --> 00:05:17,557
and how it unfolds.

112
00:05:18,017 --> 00:05:19,318
It's very important for a lot of people,

113
00:05:19,679 --> 00:05:20,860
especially in role-playing games.

114
00:05:21,741 --> 00:05:24,164
For a lot of people who came from a tabletop

115
00:05:24,284 --> 00:05:25,345
or pen and paper background,

116
00:05:25,685 --> 00:05:27,127
they really, really enjoy the ability

117
00:05:27,147 --> 00:05:29,389
to screw with the story in some ways and make it their own.

118
00:05:30,197 --> 00:05:34,379
You also grant character agency, and I want to differentiate that from story agency.

119
00:05:34,899 --> 00:05:39,881
You're not just changing the story, but you have the ability to express what type of person your character is.

120
00:05:40,462 --> 00:05:46,224
So if you're a jackass, or you're a really cool guy, or you want to smooch some girl or something, whatever,

121
00:05:46,644 --> 00:05:50,746
that's why we build that in there, to allow you to express the type of character you are.

122
00:05:50,786 --> 00:05:52,907
Not just how the story goes, but how you make it unfold.

123
00:05:53,967 --> 00:05:57,828
Also, it forces you to make tactical and strategic choices.

124
00:05:58,468 --> 00:06:03,169
Again, this is sort of ideally, this is what I'm going towards in the talk, but good dialogue

125
00:06:03,289 --> 00:06:07,230
is gameplay, and the player should look at it as a series of choices that they're making,

126
00:06:07,310 --> 00:06:09,131
short-term choices and long-term choices.

127
00:06:10,011 --> 00:06:14,732
And when it's done very well, the player feels very engaged, they're paying attention, they

128
00:06:14,772 --> 00:06:19,733
pause to think about what they want to do, they feel satisfaction and the sting of making

129
00:06:19,793 --> 00:06:23,014
sacrifices along the way, and that produces great gameplay through dialogue.

130
00:06:23,834 --> 00:06:25,936
and also it produces reactive narrative content.

131
00:06:26,276 --> 00:06:28,778
This can take place outside of the dialogue itself.

132
00:06:28,838 --> 00:06:31,860
This can be people giving what we call bark strings in the world.

133
00:06:31,880 --> 00:06:32,321
Someone saying like,

134
00:06:32,341 --> 00:06:35,363
Hey man, thanks for, you know, blowing up our town, you asshole, or whatever.

135
00:06:35,383 --> 00:06:38,325
You know, like, it's that, all that sort of rich world reactivity

136
00:06:38,505 --> 00:06:39,646
that doesn't really need to be deep.

137
00:06:40,227 --> 00:06:42,308
It just needs to be actually more widespread and shallow,

138
00:06:42,348 --> 00:06:45,050
but it makes the player feel that the world pays attention

139
00:06:45,070 --> 00:06:46,431
to the things that he or she does.

140
00:06:48,899 --> 00:06:52,440
So this talk is not about writing prose.

141
00:06:52,720 --> 00:06:53,760
There are writers' roundtables.

142
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:55,560
Actually, one's going on right now, strangely enough.

143
00:06:56,321 --> 00:06:57,941
There are great writers' roundtables that are going on.

144
00:06:58,041 --> 00:07:01,382
Obviously, Austin GDC has a bunch of cool writer stuff going on.

145
00:07:01,422 --> 00:07:05,943
This isn't really about prose and writing good dialogue

146
00:07:06,003 --> 00:07:07,343
from the perspective of aesthetics.

147
00:07:08,043 --> 00:07:09,263
It's about choices.

148
00:07:10,104 --> 00:07:12,324
The reason why I want to start with choice architecture

149
00:07:12,404 --> 00:07:15,585
is because it should come under and before prose.

150
00:07:16,685 --> 00:07:18,205
Choices inform the prose that you write.

151
00:07:18,686 --> 00:07:20,848
but choices present problems on their own.

152
00:07:20,868 --> 00:07:22,950
A lot of problems, and they need to be thought through.

153
00:07:23,731 --> 00:07:27,195
And choice is the reason to have branching dialogue in the first place,

154
00:07:27,596 --> 00:07:29,959
so it should be the place where we start to think about

155
00:07:30,239 --> 00:07:31,460
what we're doing and how we want to do it.

156
00:07:33,423 --> 00:07:36,666
So, I couldn't quite pinpoint the exact...

157
00:07:37,867 --> 00:07:41,609
time and place where sort of branching narrative became a thing.

158
00:07:41,989 --> 00:07:45,631
But one of the common things that came up was with an author, Jorge Luis Borges,

159
00:07:46,152 --> 00:07:48,453
and he wrote a book called The Garden of Forking Paths.

160
00:07:49,313 --> 00:07:51,955
And this was pretty radical at the time because

161
00:07:52,655 --> 00:07:54,957
the story could be read in a lot of different ways,

162
00:07:55,417 --> 00:07:57,498
and the reader would arrive at different conclusions

163
00:07:57,538 --> 00:07:59,139
about what the narrative was and where it went.

164
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:04,182
And someone writing a few years ago about this

165
00:08:04,980 --> 00:08:08,521
I have this cool quote that actually when I can see it on my screen I'll read out to you.

166
00:08:09,762 --> 00:08:14,364
Borges confronts us with the pullulating moment when we become aware of all the possible choices

167
00:08:14,444 --> 00:08:19,126
we might make, all the ways in which we might intersect one another for good or evil.

168
00:08:19,806 --> 00:08:23,347
His imagined garden of forking paths is both a book and a landscape,

169
00:08:23,848 --> 00:08:28,069
a book that has the shape of a labyrinth that folds back upon itself in infinite regression.

170
00:08:28,970 --> 00:08:31,772
This is the definition of sort of the possibility space for the player.

171
00:08:32,533 --> 00:08:35,756
When we empower the player to make choices and then reward them for making choices,

172
00:08:35,796 --> 00:08:38,938
they become aware of the power they have in the story and they start to embrace it.

173
00:08:39,379 --> 00:08:43,903
If we consistently reward that, they feel like they have a very strong role as a player

174
00:08:43,923 --> 00:08:47,966
in determining the outcome and they engage with the story much more than if they're just watching it,

175
00:08:48,006 --> 00:08:50,368
because they realize they're an active participant in it.

176
00:08:53,571 --> 00:08:54,391
Jeez Louise.

177
00:08:59,127 --> 00:09:00,687
This is when I actually started caring about it.

178
00:09:00,988 --> 00:09:04,930
Strangely enough, I was not reading Borges when I was five years old.

179
00:09:06,571 --> 00:09:10,813
I was reading The Cave of Time, which is my favorite of the Choose Your Own Adventure series.

180
00:09:10,833 --> 00:09:13,935
I'm curious, how many people have read Choose Your Own Adventure books?

181
00:09:14,575 --> 00:09:14,955
Yeah!

182
00:09:15,656 --> 00:09:16,796
Those are a great series of books.

183
00:09:17,277 --> 00:09:18,677
Awesome. Yes. Yes.

184
00:09:19,656 --> 00:09:24,698
So, choose-your-own-adventure books are, they're great, fantastic stuff.

185
00:09:24,898 --> 00:09:27,879
Every book is a different sort of style book or genre of book,

186
00:09:27,899 --> 00:09:29,880
but they all have that idea of branching narrative.

187
00:09:31,080 --> 00:09:33,901
However, if you were even a remotely smart kid,

188
00:09:34,761 --> 00:09:36,702
what you started to do after you read a few of these books

189
00:09:36,762 --> 00:09:40,983
was you start to put your finger in the page before you made a choice.

190
00:09:42,325 --> 00:09:46,207
And just to draw a parallel, this is not really that different from abusing a save-load mechanic.

191
00:09:47,727 --> 00:09:50,708
Which is actually a big point of some of the things I come to later.

192
00:09:51,068 --> 00:09:54,089
So, choose your own adventure books are the start of this, but even they have underlying

193
00:09:54,129 --> 00:09:57,570
problems that still persist now in branching dialogue and role-playing games.

194
00:09:59,235 --> 00:10:03,098
Then later on, I really got into role-playing games, tabletop role-playing games.

195
00:10:03,678 --> 00:10:07,081
And I played with a lot of different DMs, and I was the DM, and a lot of different players.

196
00:10:07,281 --> 00:10:10,323
And the stuff that I enjoyed the most, and the stuff my players seemed to enjoy the most,

197
00:10:11,003 --> 00:10:15,046
is when the story was constructed in such a way that the players could fuck it up.

198
00:10:15,266 --> 00:10:18,108
Basically, they could screw with it, and they could push it, and they could pull it.

199
00:10:19,189 --> 00:10:21,649
they could smack the quest giver and throw him down a well,

200
00:10:21,709 --> 00:10:24,410
and the story could keep working, and then it rolled with it,

201
00:10:24,470 --> 00:10:25,810
and that was so satisfying to them.

202
00:10:26,390 --> 00:10:28,470
And often there were consequences for doing that sort of stuff,

203
00:10:28,631 --> 00:10:31,291
but they felt very empowered in that environment,

204
00:10:31,311 --> 00:10:32,331
especially because that was just,

205
00:10:32,751 --> 00:10:34,552
it's up to the people there and their imagination.

206
00:10:34,592 --> 00:10:37,632
So that feeling can be hard to emulate in a computer environment,

207
00:10:37,652 --> 00:10:40,113
but that's what, ideally, we try to do.

208
00:10:40,193 --> 00:10:42,133
And so this had a lasting effect on me.

209
00:10:42,173 --> 00:10:43,314
I played tons of these games,

210
00:10:43,834 --> 00:10:45,994
and the most satisfying times were the ones where I was able to do that.

211
00:10:48,039 --> 00:10:52,141
Dialogue trees and RPGs, my first experience with it was with the original Fallout.

212
00:10:52,201 --> 00:10:57,625
Tim Cain gave a great post-mortem this morning on Fallout.

213
00:10:58,614 --> 00:11:02,217
I was in college when Fallout came out, and I was just enthralled with it.

214
00:11:02,257 --> 00:11:02,957
I thought it was great.

215
00:11:03,798 --> 00:11:05,039
I loved how you could make choices.

216
00:11:05,059 --> 00:11:08,521
You could be an evil character, you could be a sort of neutral character, you could

217
00:11:08,541 --> 00:11:12,684
do all sorts of different stuff, and the game didn't... it wasn't like a grand karmic wheel

218
00:11:12,724 --> 00:11:14,946
was there to smash you in the face after you made a bad choice.

219
00:11:15,246 --> 00:11:19,009
People reacted to the bad things that you did, but the game itself did not punish you.

220
00:11:19,229 --> 00:11:21,531
The designer did not punish you for playing a certain way.

221
00:11:22,939 --> 00:11:27,644
Also, when I first came to Black Isle, my first job there was as a webmaster on the

222
00:11:27,684 --> 00:11:30,227
web team, and I made the Planescape Torment website.

223
00:11:30,247 --> 00:11:34,692
I was working with the development team, and obviously Torment is very, very widely regarded

224
00:11:34,752 --> 00:11:40,218
as a great game with amazing choice and consequence, huge amount of dialogue, lots of reactivity.

225
00:11:41,639 --> 00:11:44,863
And so that had an impression on me because when I came into that environment,

226
00:11:45,304 --> 00:11:48,488
I saw these guys that were just busting ass to give them, you know,

227
00:11:48,788 --> 00:11:50,710
all this choice and consequence to the player.

228
00:11:50,770 --> 00:11:53,554
So that was the environment that I came into when I came to Black Isle.

229
00:11:55,796 --> 00:11:57,639
So, dialogue trees today.

