485
00:23:05,517 --> 00:23:06,959
and then you do some stuff for Caesar's Legion,

486
00:23:06,979 --> 00:23:08,380
and then you get points in the happy pool,

487
00:23:08,841 --> 00:23:09,841
and then eventually, you know,

488
00:23:10,302 --> 00:23:11,783
some NTR ranger comes up to you and says,

489
00:23:11,803 --> 00:23:13,725
you're gonna fucking die, bro, and shoots you.

490
00:23:14,846 --> 00:23:17,569
So it's a long-term outcome, it's a strategic decision.

491
00:23:17,669 --> 00:23:19,511
It's not about having a big scripted reaction,

492
00:23:19,551 --> 00:23:21,313
it's about a little reaction that builds up over time.

493
00:23:23,528 --> 00:23:24,870
Forecasting consequences.

494
00:23:24,970 --> 00:23:29,253
So, you know, I gave that example of the choice from Fallout 1.

495
00:23:29,753 --> 00:23:31,735
So the idea is that you want to intrigue the player.

496
00:23:32,235 --> 00:23:33,936
You don't need to spell everything out,

497
00:23:33,976 --> 00:23:36,118
but you kind of have to forecast what's going to happen.

498
00:23:36,658 --> 00:23:37,839
In a writers' roundtable yesterday,

499
00:23:37,919 --> 00:23:39,240
one of the guys gave an example of,

500
00:23:39,581 --> 00:23:40,962
I don't actually know what game he was talking about,

501
00:23:41,002 --> 00:23:43,063
but he said he picked a line that seemed like

502
00:23:43,404 --> 00:23:45,505
kind of aggressive, and then he wound up

503
00:23:45,545 --> 00:23:46,766
just like gunning a bunch of people down.

504
00:23:47,772 --> 00:23:51,474
He was like, whoa, whoa, whoa, I didn't quite want to be that aggressive.

505
00:23:52,455 --> 00:23:56,337
So intrigue the player, but inform them of generally what's going to happen.

506
00:23:56,397 --> 00:23:58,338
You can surprise them, but don't make them angry.

507
00:23:58,418 --> 00:24:03,522
So if you surprise them in a pleasant way, awesome, great, that's the joy, the joy of

508
00:24:03,582 --> 00:24:05,743
story as it unfolds.

509
00:24:06,063 --> 00:24:09,926
But don't make them mad, because then they just feel like they were sort of tricked into

510
00:24:09,946 --> 00:24:11,227
picking something that they didn't want to take.

511
00:24:12,287 --> 00:24:13,628
Differentiate the consequences.

512
00:24:13,668 --> 00:24:15,549
This is super-duper important.

513
00:24:16,970 --> 00:24:23,134
False choices, not all players pick up on them, but players are simultaneously smarter

514
00:24:23,354 --> 00:24:27,997
and dumber than we think they are, and a lot of them do pick up on fake choices.

515
00:24:28,157 --> 00:24:31,099
They sense it very quickly, especially if a game uses them a lot.

516
00:24:31,620 --> 00:24:33,601
So I would say, let's just stop doing it.

517
00:24:33,921 --> 00:24:35,242
Everybody, let's stop doing it.

518
00:24:35,282 --> 00:24:35,562
Thank you.

519
00:24:38,365 --> 00:24:39,825
Lace consequences with sacrifice.

520
00:24:40,186 --> 00:24:43,327
So, I'll get into some differences in choice agony,

521
00:24:43,807 --> 00:24:45,308
but when a person makes a choice,

522
00:24:46,409 --> 00:24:47,989
they should feel like they're making a trade-off.

523
00:24:48,430 --> 00:24:51,491
The idea with sacrifice is always that you get something more out of it than you lose,

524
00:24:51,811 --> 00:24:53,232
because that's why you made the sacrifice,

525
00:24:53,692 --> 00:24:56,033
but you should feel like you did make a trade-off there.

526
00:24:56,494 --> 00:24:57,054
And ideally...

527
00:24:57,774 --> 00:25:01,860
It's a bunch of different options where there's some pros and cons and they're not easy choices, but they don't have to be

528
00:25:02,601 --> 00:25:03,302
horribly intense

529
00:25:04,123 --> 00:25:08,329
And that push-pull conflict produces agony and that generally speaking is good when it doesn't go too far

530
00:25:10,826 --> 00:25:13,489
Validating the options of choice and consequence.

531
00:25:13,669 --> 00:25:15,451
Again, this goes back to when you make a choice,

532
00:25:15,692 --> 00:25:17,374
you want to validate it, say, yes, player,

533
00:25:17,714 --> 00:25:19,516
this is a correct way to play the game.

534
00:25:19,917 --> 00:25:21,438
You're the character you chose to play.

535
00:25:21,679 --> 00:25:22,800
We support that.

536
00:25:23,340 --> 00:25:24,442
You can keep rolling with this.

537
00:25:24,482 --> 00:25:26,024
If you make a similar choice down the road,

538
00:25:26,524 --> 00:25:27,786
it's also going to be supported.

539
00:25:27,846 --> 00:25:28,566
Keep on trucking.

540
00:25:28,667 --> 00:25:29,007
Good job.

541
00:25:31,103 --> 00:25:32,925
This is in contrast to choice and no consequence.

542
00:25:33,025 --> 00:25:34,526
I'll pick a little bit on Dragon Age here.

543
00:25:34,866 --> 00:25:36,127
Dragon Age had a lot of cool stuff in it.

544
00:25:36,588 --> 00:25:37,749
This isn't one of them, sorry.

545
00:25:38,709 --> 00:25:41,472
You have a bunch of options that people talk about

546
00:25:41,612 --> 00:25:42,552
and it doesn't produce anything.

547
00:25:42,652 --> 00:25:44,934
There's absolutely no different ending result

548
00:25:44,954 --> 00:25:46,135
from you picking any of these options.

549
00:25:46,175 --> 00:25:47,676
You can circle through it over and over again

550
00:25:48,497 --> 00:25:49,658
and it's the same outcome.

551
00:25:50,318 --> 00:25:51,679
It's kind of a waste of the player's time

552
00:25:51,820 --> 00:25:53,181
and it's a waste of the writer's time.

553
00:25:54,963 --> 00:25:55,824
We've done this in the past.

554
00:25:55,904 --> 00:25:56,304
Oh, sorry.

555
00:25:56,384 --> 00:25:56,724
Oh, jeez.

556
00:25:56,924 --> 00:25:57,664
We've done this in the past.

557
00:25:57,684 --> 00:25:59,365
A lot of companies have done this in the past.

558
00:25:59,725 --> 00:26:03,566
I think we do it because we feel that we want to give the player options, but again, players

559
00:26:03,586 --> 00:26:04,326
pick up on this stuff.

560
00:26:04,586 --> 00:26:05,586
They get irritated with it.

561
00:26:05,966 --> 00:26:09,567
If you do it a lot, they get really bored of your dialogue because they feel like the

562
00:26:09,607 --> 00:26:10,867
choices they make don't mean anything.

563
00:26:12,608 --> 00:26:13,408
Versus win and loss.

564
00:26:13,768 --> 00:26:15,609
So again, Fallout New Vegas, we did this all over the place.

565
00:26:15,649 --> 00:26:16,329
This is also bad.

566
00:26:18,370 --> 00:26:19,491
When you come into this situation,

567
00:26:20,232 --> 00:26:22,173
unless you just want to fight, which is, you know,

568
00:26:22,273 --> 00:26:24,035
you can still fight even after taking this option,

569
00:26:24,055 --> 00:26:25,456
but this option makes it incredibly easy.

570
00:26:25,836 --> 00:26:27,077
You can come in here, you have a high speech,

571
00:26:27,177 --> 00:26:27,898
and you can just say,

572
00:26:27,918 --> 00:26:30,459
hey man, I'm here to drop off some drugs, see ya.

573
00:26:30,700 --> 00:26:32,321
And then you just walk around and steal everything

574
00:26:32,341 --> 00:26:33,822
and then come back and C4 everyone

575
00:26:33,862 --> 00:26:34,623
or whatever you want to do.

576
00:26:35,783 --> 00:26:36,744
If you have a high speech,

577
00:26:37,144 --> 00:26:41,007
you're kind of like shooting yourself in the foot

578
00:26:41,027 --> 00:26:41,968
if you don't pick this option.

579
00:26:42,028 --> 00:26:43,669
So we're kind of saying like, if you don't take this,

580
00:26:44,590 --> 00:26:45,591
you're playing at a disadvantage,

581
00:26:45,851 --> 00:26:47,292
not really that great or satisfying.

582
00:26:49,015 --> 00:26:51,717
So I want to talk about choice extremes.

583
00:26:51,997 --> 00:27:05,626
So that's how to spell extremes, by the way, officially.

584
00:27:06,645 --> 00:27:10,648
So there are kind of two ends of the spectrum here, neither of which I feel are particularly great.

585
00:27:11,188 --> 00:27:12,809
One is the sort of Jesus-Hitler option.

586
00:27:13,570 --> 00:27:15,271
Again, a lot of our games have had these.

587
00:27:15,591 --> 00:27:18,773
Hopefully we've moved mostly away from these because we like moral ambiguity a lot.

588
00:27:19,273 --> 00:27:20,574
Jesus-Hitler is kind of like,

589
00:27:20,974 --> 00:27:23,956
hey, there's a baby. Do you want to give the baby a little smooch on the forehead,

590
00:27:24,056 --> 00:27:25,157
or do you want to throw it into an oven?

591
00:27:27,522 --> 00:27:32,264
And we see those options, and they're not really compelling.

592
00:27:32,524 --> 00:27:35,245
Like, if you've decided you want to play a crazy dude,

593
00:27:35,645 --> 00:27:37,786
then there's no struggle to figure out what you want to do.

594
00:27:37,806 --> 00:27:38,547
There's no sacrifice.

595
00:27:38,587 --> 00:27:40,067
Just like, well, yeah, I'm a crazy baby killer.

596
00:27:40,107 --> 00:27:40,508
There you go.

597
00:27:41,388 --> 00:27:42,869
Or no, like, I'm a super nice guy.

598
00:27:42,889 --> 00:27:43,689
Why would I ever do that?

599
00:27:44,069 --> 00:27:47,451
So there's no real interesting choice to be made there.

600
00:27:47,551 --> 00:27:48,131
It's very flat.

601
00:27:48,191 --> 00:27:50,532
It is an option, and it is differentiated, hopefully,

602
00:27:50,572 --> 00:27:51,252
in how it works out.

603
00:27:51,272 --> 00:27:52,473
But it's not that compelling.

604
00:27:53,373 --> 00:27:55,234
And then also, then the other end of the extreme

605
00:27:55,254 --> 00:27:56,035
is Sophie's Choice.

606
00:27:56,715 --> 00:27:59,777
Spoilers for a 30-some year old book.

607
00:28:01,638 --> 00:28:07,962
So yeah, Meryl Streep's character, she has to choose between which of her children will

608
00:28:08,142 --> 00:28:08,423
die.

609
00:28:10,664 --> 00:28:12,165
No one wants to make that sort of a choice in a game.

610
00:28:13,366 --> 00:28:13,926
There's no sad...

611
00:28:13,946 --> 00:28:16,268
It's not like, wow, I'm so glad I made that choice instead of that one.

612
00:28:16,308 --> 00:28:17,529
It's just two shitty choices.

613
00:28:18,069 --> 00:28:20,591
So a player should feel like there's something good.

614
00:28:21,543 --> 00:28:25,404
and bad out of what they pick. Not just like, well, which limb do I lose? Or like, which

615
00:28:25,464 --> 00:28:29,285
child do I sacrifice? Those choices, they're interesting in the sense that they produce

616
00:28:29,305 --> 00:28:33,926
some struggle, but the player really doesn't feel good about having to make those choices.

617
00:28:33,966 --> 00:28:39,367
So ideally, the agony in the conflict is somewhere between these two spectrums. It's not as simple

618
00:28:39,407 --> 00:28:43,528
as Jesus-Hitler, and it's not heart-wrenching, total loss like Sophie's choice.

619
00:28:46,138 --> 00:28:48,501
Just some examples from... actually these are kind of nasty too.

620
00:28:49,662 --> 00:28:51,224
But they're differentiated in an important way.

621
00:28:51,284 --> 00:28:53,727
So choice agony is...

622
00:28:54,247 --> 00:28:56,910
Greek plays do this really, really well and very consistently.

623
00:28:57,451 --> 00:28:58,332
Greek plays will...

624
00:28:59,013 --> 00:29:00,414
Spoilers for thousand-year-old plays.

625
00:29:04,339 --> 00:29:09,121
So in this case, the agony is not between two things that are,

626
00:29:09,701 --> 00:29:12,062
to borrow an economics term that I learned yesterday, fungible.

627
00:29:12,883 --> 00:29:15,944
They're not between like a child or this child or this arm or this arm.

628
00:29:16,464 --> 00:29:19,746
In the case of Orestes and Antigone, it's a choice between

629
00:29:20,106 --> 00:29:22,687
two kind of equally bad and equally good options,

630
00:29:22,787 --> 00:29:26,849
but the sort of value arithmetic that goes into it is not equal.

631
00:29:27,869 --> 00:29:30,410
Orestes' father was killed by his mother,

632
00:29:31,070 --> 00:29:31,891
and I think it's Apollo.

633
00:29:32,791 --> 00:29:35,412
is saying, yo, you have to avenge your dad, kill your mom.

634
00:29:35,472 --> 00:29:38,214
And the Furies are saying, dude, you cannot kill your mom.

635
00:29:38,294 --> 00:29:39,154
That is bad news.

636
00:29:39,735 --> 00:29:41,515
He's like, oh man, and he kills his mom,

637
00:29:41,535 --> 00:29:42,416
and then the Furies chase him.

638
00:29:42,516 --> 00:29:43,997
And it's, oh my god, how agonizing.

639
00:29:44,857 --> 00:29:47,238
Antigone wants to honor her brother, bury her brother.

640
00:29:47,258 --> 00:29:50,140
I think it's her dad, says, you can't do that, I forbid it.

641
00:29:50,160 --> 00:29:52,321
And she's like, wow, this is agonizing.

642
00:29:52,341 --> 00:29:53,602
And then she goes over and does it.

643
00:29:53,884 --> 00:29:56,085
So again, the value arithmetic there is not,

644
00:29:56,726 --> 00:29:58,667
oh yeah, well it's just six of one, half dozen of the other.

645
00:29:58,687 --> 00:29:59,828
It's two different things.

646
00:29:59,908 --> 00:30:01,509
And when a person reads that,

647
00:30:01,769 --> 00:30:03,590
one person might say, well, I value this more than that.

648
00:30:03,750 --> 00:30:04,590
I value this more than that.

649
00:30:04,610 --> 00:30:06,631
And that's what makes our individual choices

650
00:30:06,672 --> 00:30:08,132
more interesting, as opposed to,

651
00:30:08,172 --> 00:30:09,773
hey, what color do you dislike more?

652
00:30:11,274 --> 00:30:13,135
It's not to be confused with spice agony.

653
00:30:16,297 --> 00:30:18,398
Just so you know, choice agony is not spice agony.

654
00:30:19,019 --> 00:30:20,720
Arguably, spice agony is even cooler

655
00:30:20,760 --> 00:30:21,520
because it's from Dune.

656
00:30:22,421 --> 00:30:22,581
So.

657
00:30:24,543 --> 00:30:25,724
But it's not the same. Sorry, guys.

658
00:30:26,724 --> 00:30:27,505
So the second step...

659
00:30:28,265 --> 00:30:29,266
I guess I'm doing okay on time,

660
00:30:29,526 --> 00:30:30,687
even though I'm screwing around all the time.

661
00:30:31,908 --> 00:30:34,970
The second step is to define the range of character and player expression.

662
00:30:35,730 --> 00:30:36,571
This is really about,

663
00:30:36,631 --> 00:30:38,972
hey, what sort of characters do you want to allow people to play?

664
00:30:39,012 --> 00:30:40,954
And are you going to support through the choices that you give?

665
00:30:41,754 --> 00:30:44,695
So you want to define a response and reactivity scope.

666
00:30:44,715 --> 00:30:46,415
This means what can the player say

667
00:30:46,495 --> 00:30:47,796
and how are people going to react to it.

668
00:30:47,976 --> 00:30:48,996
It's very important to figure out.

669
00:30:49,816 --> 00:30:51,257
What sort of character prototypes?

670
00:30:51,677 --> 00:30:53,377
I'm just using, I made up that term

671
00:30:53,437 --> 00:30:54,538
because I didn't want to use archetype.

672
00:30:54,738 --> 00:30:55,378
I'll get into that later.

673
00:30:55,398 --> 00:30:57,298
What sort of character prototypes do you want to use?

674
00:30:57,738 --> 00:30:58,839
Support for character ideas.

675
00:30:59,459 --> 00:31:02,020
And then create a range of impacts that you can have.

676
00:31:02,060 --> 00:31:03,740
These can be little impacts, big impacts.

677
00:31:03,780 --> 00:31:04,840
They can be physical impacts,

678
00:31:04,880 --> 00:31:06,581
emotional impacts, all over the place.

679
00:31:08,148 --> 00:31:10,830
So figuring out the scope of responses and reactivity is very important.

680
00:31:11,930 --> 00:31:16,814
If you are making a game with very split morality, good and evil, that's your range.

681
00:31:17,214 --> 00:31:20,096
Is it about shades of gray, where there's a lot of moral ambiguity?

682
00:31:20,757 --> 00:31:23,138
Are the responses aligned along things like stance?

683
00:31:23,238 --> 00:31:25,100
So for example, Alpha Protocol had stances.

684
00:31:25,120 --> 00:31:29,162
There are a number of games that have things like stances where they're more like attitudes.

685
00:31:29,523 --> 00:31:31,104
They're not really aligned along morality.

686
00:31:33,470 --> 00:31:36,091
And then, what sort of reactivity are you going to have?

687
00:31:36,251 --> 00:31:38,613
What sort of scripted or direct reactivity are you going to have?

688
00:31:38,773 --> 00:31:42,555
And then also, what sort of indirect reputation mechanics are you going to have?

689
00:31:43,136 --> 00:31:44,497
Reputation, influence, things like that.

690
00:31:44,537 --> 00:31:47,739
So the player can get more frequent inputs into that system.

691
00:31:49,980 --> 00:31:52,161
As an example, Fallout New Vegas' scope and range.

692
00:31:53,342 --> 00:31:54,182
It was really big.

693
00:31:55,023 --> 00:31:56,983
One of the cool things about the Fallout setting is that

694
00:31:57,043 --> 00:31:58,964
there's just so much crazy stuff in it.

695
00:32:00,244 --> 00:32:01,625
And designers have a lot of fun with that.

696
00:32:01,725 --> 00:32:03,105
Players usually have a lot of fun with it.

697
00:32:03,445 --> 00:32:05,506
It doesn't always result in a consistent experience, though.

698
00:32:06,366 --> 00:32:08,767
So there's a huge scope of responses.

699
00:32:09,307 --> 00:32:10,608
Anything goes at any scale.

700
00:32:10,648 --> 00:32:12,969
So Fallout New Vegas, you couldn't kill children.

701
00:32:14,629 --> 00:32:16,289
because I don't think any games allow you to do that anymore,

702
00:32:16,369 --> 00:32:18,070
but you can kill everyone else.

703
00:32:18,350 --> 00:32:19,170
Like, everyone.

704
00:32:19,850 --> 00:32:21,731
What I told the designers is that you have to imagine

705
00:32:21,751 --> 00:32:25,191
that the player has a, like, Thanatos kill field around them

706
00:32:25,231 --> 00:32:26,612
everywhere they go, and they just can't help it.

707
00:32:26,652 --> 00:32:27,792
They just— everyone drops dead.

708
00:32:28,372 --> 00:32:31,433
So, so, the whole game was structured

709
00:32:31,453 --> 00:32:32,593
so that you could kill everyone.

710
00:32:33,093 --> 00:32:35,194
Even your one sort of fall-through guy,

711
00:32:35,214 --> 00:32:36,394
you could kill him, and he died,

712
00:32:36,454 --> 00:32:38,614
but he would then transfer his consciousness

713
00:32:38,634 --> 00:32:39,975
into a different robot and come up to you.

714
00:32:40,035 --> 00:32:42,095
So, it was very important that we allowed that.

715
00:32:43,355 --> 00:32:47,979
Also, you can do all this crazy reverse triple betrayal stuff.

716
00:32:48,619 --> 00:32:50,621
Because of our reputation mechanics and the way that they worked,

717
00:32:51,021 --> 00:32:54,164
you could start out working for NCR, and then kind of drift over to Caesar's Legion,

718
00:32:54,204 --> 00:32:55,985
and then get on their good side, and then,

719
00:32:56,085 --> 00:32:57,666
oh, we're actually going to help out Mr. House,

720
00:32:57,686 --> 00:32:59,328
and then we're going to betray him and go independent.

721
00:32:59,348 --> 00:33:02,310
So there's a lot of things and ways that you could weave through the story.

722
00:33:03,071 --> 00:33:06,353
There's a lot of scripted reactivity, like a crazy amount of scripted reactivity.

723
00:33:06,874 --> 00:33:10,716
And all the credit for that goes to the writing team and the area designers that made that stuff happen.

724
00:33:11,724 --> 00:33:15,592
And reputation, we had a reputation system for factions and for locations and that served

725
00:33:15,632 --> 00:33:19,642
as our indirect system where players would either perform actions or do dialogue things

726
00:33:19,702 --> 00:33:21,446
and resolve quests to feed into that system.

727
00:33:23,424 --> 00:33:25,686
So now I want to talk about prototypes.

728
00:33:25,926 --> 00:33:27,568
Again, I use this word instead of archetypes

729
00:33:27,648 --> 00:33:30,070
because I think that sometimes archetypes get,

730
00:33:30,310 --> 00:33:31,491
that word kind of gets thrown around.

731
00:33:31,952 --> 00:33:33,553
Archetype is higher level than these guys.

732
00:33:33,633 --> 00:33:35,014
Archetypes are more abstracted

733
00:33:35,054 --> 00:33:36,355
than these individual characters.

734
00:33:37,276 --> 00:33:39,378
Prototypes to me in a role-playing game

735
00:33:39,598 --> 00:33:41,540
are starting points for character concepts.

736
00:33:41,760 --> 00:33:42,801
They can be sole characters,

737
00:33:42,821 --> 00:33:46,084
sometimes they're combinations of characters.

738
00:33:46,184 --> 00:33:47,005
I want to play Aragorn.

739
00:33:47,225 --> 00:33:48,186
I want to play Snake Plissken.

740
00:33:51,851 --> 00:33:54,916
I want to play Clint Eastwood's racist character from Gran Torino.

741
00:33:56,938 --> 00:33:59,923
By the way, I really want to make an RPG where someone's like,

742
00:34:00,083 --> 00:34:01,725
yes, I'm playing Clint Eastwood in Gran Torino.

743
00:34:04,042 --> 00:34:08,125
The idea is that players really, they like, they gravitate towards these characters and

744
00:34:08,205 --> 00:34:10,547
players are creative but we all start somewhere.

745
00:34:10,707 --> 00:34:14,610
And so some players will be like, yeah I want to be the man with no name, I want to be Elizabeth

746
00:34:14,630 --> 00:34:17,572
Salander from, you know, Girl with the Dragon Tattoo, I want to be Blade, whatever.

747
00:34:17,813 --> 00:34:21,055
There's a starting point and then over time they usually expand from there.

748
00:34:21,095 --> 00:34:25,058
But understanding what your game and your genre supports and where it's going to start

749
00:34:25,178 --> 00:34:25,899
is very helpful.

750
00:34:26,439 --> 00:34:30,262
It's not just useful for defining dialogue but other things like dress and appearance

751
00:34:30,282 --> 00:34:31,523
and costuming and things like that.

752
00:34:32,224 --> 00:34:37,348
In fact, in New Vegas, the number of clothing mods you see for people that are supporting

753
00:34:37,388 --> 00:34:37,629
the man...

754
00:34:37,709 --> 00:34:38,369
Like, everyone's,

755
00:34:38,389 --> 00:34:39,410
Hey, I'm the man with no name.

756
00:34:39,610 --> 00:34:40,872
Great, I'm Clint Eastwood in New Vegas.

757
00:34:40,952 --> 00:34:41,152
Great.

758
00:34:41,212 --> 00:34:43,534
There's like a zillion different clothing packs that support that.

759
00:34:44,115 --> 00:34:46,617
So understanding what people are going to want to play is very important.

760
00:34:48,440 --> 00:34:49,921
What are the Fallout New Vegas prototypes?

761
00:34:50,542 --> 00:34:51,162
Who knows?

762
00:34:51,322 --> 00:34:53,563
Because we didn't define them ahead of time, unfortunately.

763
00:34:54,024 --> 00:34:57,466
We knew we were going to have a huge range of influences

764
00:34:57,986 --> 00:35:00,948
and responses, but we didn't really sit down and think of

765
00:35:00,988 --> 00:35:02,168
this ahead of time, unfortunately.

766
00:35:02,769 --> 00:35:05,850
So yeah, there's some stuff where you kind of feel like

767
00:35:05,870 --> 00:35:06,631
the man with no name.

768
00:35:07,932 --> 00:35:10,013
Or you also kind of think about, you feel like Mad Max.

769
00:35:10,173 --> 00:35:10,653
Surprise!

770
00:35:10,693 --> 00:35:11,534
These are the same character.

771
00:35:12,354 --> 00:35:13,955
One is in Australia, one's in the United States.

772
00:35:14,415 --> 00:35:15,836
They're kind of the same dude, though.

773
00:35:17,629 --> 00:35:22,555
And there's some stuff where you feel kind of like this weird spec ops guy that's that beard guy.

774
00:35:22,875 --> 00:35:23,997
You know who I'm talking about.

775
00:35:24,017 --> 00:35:25,598
It's that beard guy.

776
00:35:27,461 --> 00:35:27,621
And...

777
00:35:27,641 --> 00:35:31,145
Oh, I know he has a real name, but everyone knows him as that beard guy.

778
00:35:32,570 --> 00:35:34,751
but you know that but we don't really fully support it and there's other

779
00:35:34,772 --> 00:35:37,033
things that we could have supported post-apocalyptic characters

780
00:35:37,673 --> 00:35:39,034
like all the crazy tribal

781
00:35:40,054 --> 00:35:42,775
people from doomsday or even the like the tribal kids from

782
00:35:43,496 --> 00:35:44,716
beyond thunderdome and stuff like that

783
00:35:45,177 --> 00:35:47,718
but we didn't really think about it also there are other examples of like

784
00:35:47,958 --> 00:35:49,839
strong female characters like Alice from the

785
00:35:50,139 --> 00:35:52,620
Resident Evil series could be considered a post-apocalyptic character

786
00:35:53,441 --> 00:35:55,962
but we didn't really think through like what what are we trying to support

787
00:35:56,102 --> 00:35:56,842
unfortunately so

788
00:35:57,223 --> 00:35:58,443
the range of responses was

789
00:35:59,124 --> 00:36:01,672
Granted in the Fallout universe they're already all over the place but they didn't really

790
00:36:01,692 --> 00:36:04,079
feel like you were playing a consistent character necessarily.

791
00:36:05,297 --> 00:36:06,597
You want to create a range of impacts.

792
00:36:07,458 --> 00:36:08,739
Choices should have impact.

793
00:36:09,199 --> 00:36:12,081
Again, this goes back to don't just kind of make fluff or meaningless choices.

794
00:36:12,461 --> 00:36:15,143
You want to ground them and make the player feel like, wow, I'm cool.

795
00:36:15,223 --> 00:36:17,704
Like that actually did something. It wasn't just sort of an aesthetic change.

796
00:36:18,505 --> 00:36:21,567
You can also make that happen through indirect reaction systems.

797
00:36:21,587 --> 00:36:22,447
When the player sees...

798
00:36:22,968 --> 00:36:24,088
And some people complain about this.

799
00:36:24,589 --> 00:36:25,029
Tough shit.

800
00:36:25,609 --> 00:36:27,951
When I say like, plus one to reputation, you know...

801
00:36:27,971 --> 00:36:29,972
I know it's not... it's my immersion.

802
00:36:30,672 --> 00:36:34,295
gets broken, but you see, hey, that actually fed into the system.

803
00:36:34,535 --> 00:36:35,596
Great. It's good feedback.

804
00:36:36,016 --> 00:36:38,037
So as game designers, even though some people get all

805
00:36:38,378 --> 00:36:40,739
worked up about it, it's very good to reward people that way.

806
00:36:41,580 --> 00:36:43,961
And then, the important thing, I think, to remember is that

807
00:36:44,041 --> 00:36:46,183
narrative or emotional impact is the important scale.

808
00:36:46,203 --> 00:36:49,925
These are examples of two big impacts from Fallout New Vegas.

809
00:36:51,039 --> 00:36:54,121
One is Archimedes, too, this big space laser, and that was in all the trailers.

810
00:36:55,022 --> 00:36:57,503
I don't really think that choice had a big emotional impact on a lot of people.

811
00:36:58,584 --> 00:37:02,227
The only person that has a strong emotional reaction to it is one of the companions, Arcade,

812
00:37:02,307 --> 00:37:05,389
and it's pretty unlikely that you actually have him at that point.

813
00:37:06,529 --> 00:37:09,051
It doesn't really influence a lot of things around it, so even though it's like a big event...

814
00:37:09,782 --> 00:37:11,284
there's not a lot of emotional strength to it.

815
00:37:11,404 --> 00:37:13,787
So it's like, wow, the crazy space laser, I don't care.

816
00:37:13,807 --> 00:37:15,089
I'm just going to go on with my adventure.

817
00:37:16,291 --> 00:37:18,473
Compare this to, I think, the DLC, especially all the DL...

818
00:37:18,574 --> 00:37:20,336
So I did one of the DLCs, Honest Hearts.

819
00:37:21,157 --> 00:37:23,059
I'm only putting up here because this is the one that I did, but...

820
00:37:24,161 --> 00:37:26,604
Chris Avalon was the project director on all the other DLCs

821
00:37:26,664 --> 00:37:28,526
other than Gunrunner's Arsenal, and they had great...

822
00:37:29,327 --> 00:37:30,627
emotional content to them.

823
00:37:30,787 --> 00:37:32,367
People really connected with the characters,

824
00:37:32,707 --> 00:37:33,628
did a great job there.

825
00:37:34,688 --> 00:37:36,788
In Honest Hearts, you know, the sort of resolution of it,

826
00:37:36,828 --> 00:37:38,649
people seem to respond very strongly to

827
00:37:38,689 --> 00:37:40,489
because it was a very tense moment between, really,

828
00:37:40,509 --> 00:37:41,930
just three people in a very small space.

829
00:37:42,670 --> 00:37:44,030
But that sort of stuff can go a long way.

830
00:37:44,090 --> 00:37:45,970
So the scale is really about emotional impact

831
00:37:46,811 --> 00:37:47,591
when it comes to change.

832
00:37:47,771 --> 00:37:49,331
When the player feels like they're producing something

833
00:37:49,351 --> 00:37:50,692
that really tugs at them...

834
00:37:50,712 --> 00:37:52,392
I keep doing this and I shouldn't...

835
00:37:53,772 --> 00:37:56,093
that it makes them feel good about the choices that they make.

836
00:37:57,876 --> 00:38:02,438
Something I think was much better defined in terms of scope and prototype characters was alpha protocol.

837
00:38:02,458 --> 00:38:03,478
It was very clearly defined.

838
00:38:03,898 --> 00:38:07,280
So, they had the professional and suave and aggressive stances.

839
00:38:07,700 --> 00:38:09,500
There were variants to that that would appear in dialogue,

840
00:38:09,540 --> 00:38:12,602
but that's pretty much what was established for the spectrum of responses.

841
00:38:12,622 --> 00:38:15,823
A lot of heavily scripted reactivity.

842
00:38:16,182 --> 00:38:18,804
They also had a reputation mechanic that was used very frequently.

843
00:38:19,805 --> 00:38:22,087
And they had three prototypes. It took a while to settle on this,

844
00:38:22,167 --> 00:38:23,988
but it was called the Three JBs.

845
00:38:24,489 --> 00:38:26,270
Jason Bourne, James Bond, Jack Bauer.

846
00:38:26,891 --> 00:38:32,635
Equipment choices, dialogue options, all that sort of stuff kind of fed into that.

847
00:38:32,715 --> 00:38:35,738
It's like, if I want to play like Jason Bourne, I'm going to want to say this sort of thing.

848
00:38:36,138 --> 00:38:39,920
If I want to play like Jack Bauer, I'm going to smack this guy in the face and get all aggro on him.

849
00:38:41,381 --> 00:38:43,562
And that really helped drive a lot of the choice.

850
00:38:43,602 --> 00:38:45,303
People were like, oh, okay, yeah, yeah, I get those guys.

851
00:38:45,764 --> 00:38:47,805
This is the space that we're working in, which is very important.

852
00:38:49,886 --> 00:38:51,967
So step three is about establishing narrative goals.

853
00:38:53,728 --> 00:38:57,371
Ideally, you should fuse information and emotional content, not do info dumps.

854
00:38:58,305 --> 00:39:01,871
You should separate your critical information from optional information.

855
00:39:01,951 --> 00:39:05,376
This is very important when you remember, hey, players can go around smacking dudes

856
00:39:05,456 --> 00:39:09,041
and skipping over stuff and short-cutting all sorts of things in dialogue.

857
00:39:09,482 --> 00:39:11,325
And you want to outline your narrative branching ahead of time.

858
00:39:13,213 --> 00:39:14,534
A lot of people look at New Vegas,

859
00:39:15,115 --> 00:39:16,396
maybe not everyone, but a lot of people look at it

860
00:39:16,416 --> 00:39:18,117
and they go like, wow, how did you plan all that stuff out?

861
00:39:18,197 --> 00:39:20,259
And it's actually, I don't want to say it's easy,

862
00:39:20,399 --> 00:39:21,660
but when you do it from the beginning,

863
00:39:22,281 --> 00:39:23,461
it is not especially hard.

864
00:39:23,942 --> 00:39:26,404
If you try to do it six months down the road, forget it.

865
00:39:27,224 --> 00:39:28,045
Any game that I've worked on

866
00:39:28,085 --> 00:39:29,586
where we've planned for the stuff ahead of time,

867
00:39:30,287 --> 00:39:31,428
it's gone very, very smoothly.

868
00:39:32,148 --> 00:39:33,309
Once you start developing the game

869
00:39:33,349 --> 00:39:35,271
and you try to back into a bunch of freedom

870
00:39:35,311 --> 00:39:38,593
of play and movement and choice, it doesn't go so well.

871
00:39:41,455 --> 00:39:42,216
So don't do this.

872
00:39:44,354 --> 00:39:49,918
Dialog branching is, I think, at its weakest when it comes down to essentially being no more than a keyword list,

873
00:39:49,938 --> 00:39:52,660
where you're saying, hey, tell me about this, tell me about this, tell me about this.

874
00:39:54,462 --> 00:39:55,783
I think there are much better ways to do it.

875
00:39:55,963 --> 00:39:59,365
I think that Mass Effect putting stuff in the codex is a really good way to do it,

876
00:39:59,465 --> 00:40:01,487
other than the XP gain, which I think should be gotten rid of.

877
00:40:02,348 --> 00:40:04,429
Also, Bioshock does it really well.

878
00:40:04,529 --> 00:40:07,652
They have, like, essentially three levels of interaction where there's the main storyline,

879
00:40:08,052 --> 00:40:11,254
there's the stuff you can hear through all the tape recorders and things like that.

880
00:40:11,695 --> 00:40:12,675
Thank you for reminding me of that.

881
00:40:13,096 --> 00:40:13,756
And then also the...

882
00:40:15,619 --> 00:40:19,803
all the posters and things where you can infer and imply all sorts of other relationships by looking around.

883
00:40:20,264 --> 00:40:23,267
So there are other ways to give information about the world and what's going on in it

884
00:40:23,608 --> 00:40:25,550
than just info-dumping onto the player.

885
00:40:27,151 --> 00:40:29,574
If you can give information about the world to the player,

886
00:40:29,894 --> 00:40:32,577
try to sort of wrap it inside the emotional content of something else.

887
00:40:32,617 --> 00:40:34,199
So a character is talking about something...

888
00:40:35,215 --> 00:40:36,076
that's important to them.

889
00:40:36,316 --> 00:40:38,037
And in the context of talking about that thing,

890
00:40:38,638 --> 00:40:39,758
you're learning about the world.

891
00:40:40,139 --> 00:40:41,439
If you just have someone sort of stand there

892
00:40:41,479 --> 00:40:42,860
and dryly tell you about the world,

893
00:40:42,960 --> 00:40:44,742
they're just a narrator for an encyclopedia,

894
00:40:44,782 --> 00:40:45,582
and that gets really boring.

895
00:40:47,217 --> 00:40:50,759
You have to figure out what your critical and optional information is going to be in the game.

896
00:40:52,280 --> 00:40:55,963
Again, very few players want information dumps and dialogue.

897
00:40:56,924 --> 00:40:59,686
Most players, they do want to understand what's going on.

898
00:41:00,746 --> 00:41:03,208
Usually they're skipping through things because it goes on for too long

899
00:41:03,248 --> 00:41:05,490
and tries to tell them much more than they actually need to know.

900
00:41:07,131 --> 00:41:10,433
If you write your story well, the player should not need to know a huge amount of information

901
00:41:10,453 --> 00:41:12,194
to understand the meat of the plot.

902
00:41:13,235 --> 00:41:16,858
And they really shouldn't need to know much about what they're doing in the next stage of their adventure.

903
00:41:18,267 --> 00:41:22,231
By the way, hints and hanging references, those are also exposition.

904
00:41:22,311 --> 00:41:24,513
A person can reference something without defining it.

905
00:41:25,013 --> 00:41:26,234
That's fine, let it go.

906
00:41:26,435 --> 00:41:29,478
Like, let it hang there, the person will be intrigued, look it up later,

907
00:41:29,518 --> 00:41:32,481
maybe another character references that group or organization or religion later.

908
00:41:32,921 --> 00:41:33,982
Maybe it's never defined.

909
00:41:34,302 --> 00:41:35,824
And the player goes, huh, I wonder what that is.

910
00:41:36,464 --> 00:41:39,127
I've gotten so many questions for Fallout New Vegas.

911
00:41:40,028 --> 00:41:42,570
Because Chief Hanlon, Chris Christopherson's character, says,

912
00:41:42,770 --> 00:41:45,492
yeah, all the veteran rangers are hunting ghosts down in Baja.

913
00:41:46,052 --> 00:41:48,414
And it's like, every week I get two or three people saying,

914
00:41:48,934 --> 00:41:49,774
what is he talking about?

915
00:41:50,495 --> 00:41:52,016
I am never going to tell you what that is.

916
00:41:52,476 --> 00:41:53,177
Never, never, never.

917
00:41:53,737 --> 00:41:55,218
Like, something weird's going on down there.

918
00:41:55,238 --> 00:41:56,759
They're in Baja, that sounds mysterious.

919
00:41:56,819 --> 00:41:57,800
Great, just let it go.

920
00:41:58,040 --> 00:41:58,981
That's a side thing.

921
00:41:59,521 --> 00:42:00,362
Cool, that's intriguing.

922
00:42:01,818 --> 00:42:05,401
Narrative branching. Obviously you have to guarantee that all the critical information

923
00:42:05,441 --> 00:42:09,804
is communicated. If you allow the player to do something that breaks their understanding

924
00:42:09,824 --> 00:42:15,269
of the game, that is very bad. You have to have ways to handle that. You want to isolate

925
00:42:15,289 --> 00:42:20,553
reactivity. So reactivity is awesome, and players love reactivity. I think a trap people

926
00:42:20,573 --> 00:42:22,755
fall into is they want to make the reactivity really...

927
00:42:24,476 --> 00:42:27,278
huge ripple effect from any, like a pebble hits the water and

928
00:42:27,718 --> 00:42:30,340
you know like thousands of people are changed forever and it's

929
00:42:30,840 --> 00:42:33,882
very messy. Players don't actually notice it or appreciate it. It causes a lot of bugs.

930
00:42:34,582 --> 00:42:38,245
You can actually do a lot of more like very localized reactivity

931
00:42:38,845 --> 00:42:41,327
and players feel like the world is very rich with the reactivity

932
00:42:41,647 --> 00:42:44,929
but it's very light scripting and bug fixing wise.

933
00:42:45,963 --> 00:42:48,483
And then generally speaking, more branching is better than bigger branches.

934
00:42:48,784 --> 00:42:53,725
So it's more interesting to have little ways to alter the story

935
00:42:53,825 --> 00:42:57,706
and then feed into other things than to try to make one big, massive narrative

936
00:42:57,746 --> 00:42:59,146
that branches out in a million different ways.

937
00:43:00,346 --> 00:43:05,148
Just recombinant-wise, it becomes very difficult to manage that stuff and to bug-fix it.

938
00:43:06,488 --> 00:43:08,588
So here's an example from Fallout New Vegas.

939
00:43:09,551 --> 00:43:10,712
but I think worked pretty darn well.

940
00:43:11,733 --> 00:43:14,055
They Went That-A-Way was the first main quest that you go on.

941
00:43:14,155 --> 00:43:15,817
So, Fallen to Vegas starts with you being shot in the head

942
00:43:15,917 --> 00:43:16,918
and dropped in a shallow grave,

943
00:43:17,278 --> 00:43:18,959
and your first quest is to go find the people that did it.

944
00:43:20,421 --> 00:43:23,443
So, your first steps are completely informational

945
00:43:23,483 --> 00:43:24,684
and independent of each other.

946
00:43:25,345 --> 00:43:27,247
It's really just, where did this dude go?

947
00:43:27,267 --> 00:43:29,549
It's Benny, the guy in the crazy checkered suit.

948
00:43:29,589 --> 00:43:30,089
Where did he go?

949
00:43:31,070 --> 00:43:32,631
And you go from step to step,

950
00:43:32,712 --> 00:43:34,273
and each person tells you something more

951
00:43:34,493 --> 00:43:35,734
that you follow and follow and follow.

952
00:43:36,665 --> 00:43:40,116
Because they're just information and they're independent of each other, the player can

953
00:43:40,256 --> 00:43:42,263
actually go straight to New Vegas from Goodsprings.

954
00:43:43,381 --> 00:43:45,163
without ever going into any of the other steps.

955
00:43:45,823 --> 00:43:46,884
They can do things in different orders.

956
00:43:46,924 --> 00:43:48,425
They can go straight to Novak through a pass.

957
00:43:48,846 --> 00:43:50,227
They can go to Boulder City.

958
00:43:50,667 --> 00:43:51,969
They can do things in all sorts of different order

959
00:43:52,009 --> 00:43:53,110
because the story still makes sense.

960
00:43:53,410 --> 00:43:55,932
The story is, find out who shot me and where that person is.

961
00:43:56,573 --> 00:43:58,334
If you just walk into Vegas, the story still makes sense.

962
00:43:59,095 --> 00:44:00,496
You miss little side details.

963
00:44:00,556 --> 00:44:02,458
Actually, you miss quite a few side details along the way,

964
00:44:02,918 --> 00:44:04,239
but the story is flexible.

965
00:44:04,620 --> 00:44:07,022
And by the way, we just totally ripped off Fallout 1 for this.

966
00:44:07,042 --> 00:44:08,863
We just ripped it right off.

967
00:44:09,043 --> 00:44:09,744
